<p class="definition" data-word = 'Angular Position'>
    <strong>Angular Position</strong> is given by the position of a rotating
    object on the unit circle, as measured in radians.
    <br>
    Angular Position is represented by the Greek lettr theta: \( \theta \).
</p>

<h5>
    A Brief Guide to Angular Positions
</h5>

<ul>
    <li>
        The positive-x direction, directly to the right of the center of the circle,
        represents angular position zero.
    </li>
    <li>
        As you move counterclockwise through quadrant 1,
        angular position increases to \( \frac{\pi}{2} \).
    </li>
    <li>
        The positive-y direction, directly up from the center of the circle,
        represents angular position \( \frac{\pi}{2} \).
    </li>
    <li>
        As you move counterclockwise through quadrant 2,
        angular position increases to \( \pi \).
    </li>
    <li>
        The negative-x direction, directly left from the center of the circle,
        represents angular position \( \pi \).
    </li>
    <li>
        As you move counterclockwise through quadrant 3,
        angular position increases to \( \frac{3 \pi}{2} \).
    </li>
    <li>
        The negative-y direction, directly down from the center of the circle,
        represents angular position \( \frac{3 \pi}{2} \)
    </li>
    <li>
        As you move counterclockwise through quadrant 4,
        angular position increases to \( 2 \pi \).
    </li>
    <li>
        Angular position cannot be greater than \( 2 \pi \), or a single revolution.
        Once an object crosses the +x direciton, the zero radian line,
        angular position decreases back to zero and begins again.
        (\( 2 \pi = 6.283 \))
    </li>
</ul>


